This change was intentional, but we certainly don't want to cause a performance hit like this. I assume you have a somewhat large nginx configuration?

(If you're curious, what's going on here is we're preparing to allow plugins to perform opt in enhancements to your server configuration any time `certbot renew` is run. Examples of these include adding a HSTS header whose `max-age` value slowly increases over time as the sysadmin becomes more confident it's working correctly and prefetching OCSP responses to work around some issues with Apache's and Nginx's implementation of this.)

@joohoi, we should think about this. We can eliminate some issues by not calling `prepare()` until we see the plugin implements an updater, but when a plugin does such as Apache now with AutoHSTS, configurations like this using the same plugin for many domains will have the same performance issues.

@bollwyvl, re. the open tickets for the 4.2 milestone: our typical process is to, once the desired release timeframe is coming around or if all the 'big things' are done, we look again at the open tickets targeted to this milestone. And at that point, we take a much more hard-nosed view of things: unless it can *really* get done very quickly or it's absolutely critical for the release, then we just bump it to the next one.

In that sense, all our targeted issues are a list of what we *want* to see in a release, but we don't necessarily hold a release forever just b/c one issue may not be finished.

I think we're reaching that point where a quick triage-and-bump pass is needed, so we're left with what we actually need to consider blockers for 4.2.  Otherwise, we'll never see it out :)

