@chihuahua thanks for explaining the subtleties of problem 0, there's clearly a bit more to the problem.

Re: the group op idea - does that still apply even when max_outputs is passed and is a known value at op creation time?  While max_outputs is user-specified, at least in the current code it seems like you have to specify *some* finite non-negative value.  I'd have thought maybe you could basically do `for in in range(max_outputs): summary_group.append(tensor_summary(images[i]))`, but of course to handle images tensors with fewer than max_outputs samples you'd have to be able to dynamically skip those tensor_summary ops (or dynamically insert some dummy/placeholder value, which has other issues) and perhaps that's not really feasible?

That said, even if that doesn't work I think there are other methods that would, they'd just require some special-casing in SummaryDbWriter (and actually, this special casing would make it more closely match SummaryFileWriter which does output multiple tags for multiple samples).  We'd detect the images plugin metadata in the WriteTensor() call and unpack the single tensor into separate tags upon writing to the DB.  Or alternatively with the special column idea, we'd count the samples and UPDATE Tags.sample_count to MAX(Tags.sample_count, new_sample_count).

