Well, if I had to choose between few extra records in my `world` and a _suddenly_ broken program that is crucial to all my websites, I'd prefer first.

Besides, for most Gentoo systems "polluting" actually comes down to just three packages out of [eight](https://github.com/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/blob/4d4cfb414f2847f1814cfe2949c6e76f112e4ade/letsencrypt-auto#L319) — `dev-python/virtualenv`, `app-admin/augeas` and `dev-util/dialog`, because the remaining five are already installed:

- `dev-libs/libffi` (via `virtual/libffi`) — is required by python;
- python (`dev-lang/python:2.7`) is required by portage itself;
- `virtual/pkgconfig` — by gcc, glibc and dozens of other major packages;
- `dev-libs/openssl` and `app-misc/ca-certificates` — ahem, obviously.

That being said, the list of packages `emerge`'d by `letsencrypt-auto` can (and should IMO) be reduced to 3.

> Ideally, one should use the official Gentoo package

I tried to, but quickly realized that `-auto` is totally enough for my needs. And, speaking of pollution, `-auto` adds just 3 packages to my system, while the official package wants to add 43. Oh, and 9 lines to my `/etc/portage/package.keywords`. No, thank you.

